column168: It was discovered at the point of delivery that an air valve constructed of schedule 80 PVC had slightly cracked and allowed a spill to occur at the unloading facility. The vessel was secured, the residual product neutralized and the remainder was safely off-loaded. the damaged valve/piping  was removed from the trailer and the opening was capped to avoid any further leakage hazard. The release was determined to be approx. 8 gallons per scales on-site.
column169: The tanker trailer is being sent to a repair facility that has agreed to diagnose the apparent weakness in the air valve assembly and fabricate a new air valve assembly to prevent a recurrence.

column168: While about 30 minutes from consignee location driver noticed a small drip coming from trailer.  More than 2 hours from terminal, driver was instructed to obtain some floor absorbent material and place around area of trailer floor and assure no more was escaping from unit and go on to consignee who would have better methods of cleaning the area of the trailer.  Upon arrival found freight on skid was too much for skid to handle and skid had collapsed in the middle allowing several cases of freight to be crushed.  Only 1 gallon of material was lost.  Consignee accepted freight and assisted with a minor clean up.
column169: Shippers and drivers need to communicate more on the importance of proper shipping and loading techniques, especially when dealing with transporting hazardous materials.  Drivers do not like upsetting customers, but when it comes to handling something like this, the initial pick up driver should have noticed there was too much weight on the skid and arranged for the freight to be broken down on to two or more skids.

column168: This freight was picked up in New Jersey destined for Brampton, ON. ABF carried it to Ontario where it was then reconsigned back to the warehouse in New Jersey. During the return trip back to New Jersey, a pallet was being removed from the trailer. The dockman went into the skid and did not realize that the backside of the skid was broke and a pail was resting on the trailer floor.  He believes that he punctured it;however, upon inspection, the particle board skid was already broken because somebody from a previous terminal threw the broken part of the skid in between the drums (see photos on cs-3).
column169: Heavier skids (not particle board) should be used for freight especially if it weighs almost 3000 pounds.  If freight was previously damaged as noted by 026, recoup and put on new skid or turn the skid around so that the dockman can see the drum that was on the floor and then he won't try to enter.

column168: When driver arrived at unloading destination, the customer unloader hooked up the trailer discharge hose to storage tank inlet valve, opened the trailer QRB valve, started to open the trailer hydraulic valve and product started spraying from the QRB valve body clamp.  Our driver saw the problem and closed the hydraulic valve, stopping the leak.  Upon inspection, it was noted that the wing nut on the QRB valve clamp was cross threaded, thereby not allowing it to completely tighten around the valve allowing for the product to spray out.  Our driver was able to reposition the wing nut and tighten it down so that the unloading was completed without further incident.  The clamp an wing nut were replaced at our shop when our driver returned to his terminal.

column168: During an audit of the hazardous materials shipment in container CAXU974800 loaded on booking WEB181682, 1 carton marked with class 2.1 labels was discovered.  The carton contained cylinders of Compressed Gas NOS, (Nitrogen/Oxygen), 2.2, UN1956 and was not listed on the shipper's dangerous goods declaration.  Subsequent review indicated that the class 2.2 cargo would have been incompatible with the class 3 cargo that was also loaded in the container.  The container was placarded with a class 3 and a class 8 placard to coincide with the dangerous goods declaration listing the adhesives, paint, batteries and battery fluid acid.  There were also 1 carton of battery fluid acid declared but in fact there was 3 cartons but the weight remained the same.  The customer was notified and the incompatible cargo was removed and picked up by the customer.
column169: The customer must take the time to audit his packing list against his dangerous goods declaration to ensure compliance.  He must also perform a good compatibility check to ensure that all the cargo will go in the same container without a conflict.

column168: The customer tendered the cargo with a dangerous goods declaration to the trucker and to the Steam Ship Line, Horizon Lines.  The cargo was loaded to the vessel when the customer phoned to notify the terminal of additional hazardous materials in the container.  They then faxed over corrected documentation.  Other cargo already declared was a class 5.1 organic peroxide UN3109.  The additional cargo was a class 5.1 organic peroxide UN3106.  There were no compatibility or placarding issues to address.  The updated shipping paper was received and the cargo moved to destination.
column169: The customer must take the time to audit his packing list against his bill of lading.  The international market has a 24 hour advance manifesting requirement.  If this was applied to the domestic market, time would be allowed to correct any descrepencies prior to loading the cargo on board a cargo ship.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred. After unloading, one wet cardboard box was discovered on the loading dock of the BAX Global, Inc. facility. Upon inspection it was determined that while unloading one container inside the cardboard box had been crushed. Approximately, one quart of free product was released. BAX Global, Inc. personnel used absorbent pads to contain the free product. The absorbent pads were placed into a plastic bag provided by the on site spill kit. Environmental Contractors of Illinois responded to assist with repackaging of spent material. The spent material was placed into a five gallon container and transported back to Environmental Contractors of Illinois facility where disposition will be coordinated. No injuries or exposures were reported. The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: During the unloading of the drums a forklift driver punctured one drum. The hole was 1/3 way up from the bottom of the barrel about 6 inches wide. The drum was turned on its side after 18 gallons spilled out. The spill was contained with sand and the drum was placed in a containment drum. The sand was placed in a containment vessel as well. A hazardous material recovery company was contacted and they moved the damaged vessel into another containment drum for transportation to a hazardous waste site.
column169: A safety meeting was held with the dock personnel to make them aware of the hazards of unloading hazardous materials and the need for extreme caution. Also retrained them on how to unload drums with a forklift.

column168: South Kentucky Purchasing vehicle, carrier, was travelling on Bon Hollow road.  The carrier was being driven by Carson Brewster, an employ of South Kentucky Purchasing, Inc.  Carrier was making a left turn on to a narrow road when the trailer dropped off the roadway.  Rear tires of trailer fell into a ditch causing trailer to overturn.  The carrier came to rest on the unmanned vehicle, Chevey 1993 Blazer.  The carrier was uprighted by two wreckers.  The carrier was inspected and found that the integrity of the tank had not been compromised and was still structually sound.  The contents of the carrier was off loaded, on site, onto another one of South Kentucky Purchasing Inc.'s carriers.  The damaged carrier and the unmanned vehicle were hauled off site.  There was no release of the contents of the carrier.  Somerset Environmental Services, Inc. was on site in the event of a release.  Bill Belcher, Environmental Control Supervisor for Kentucky Department for Environmental Protection (KYDEP) was onsite.  Somerset Environmental Services, Inc. repaired the road caused by the overturned carrier.
column169: South Ky Purchasing, Inc. has conducted an interview with the driver for determining the cause of the accident.  South Ky Purchasing has re-advised their drivers in the necessity for practicing safe driving habits.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: Drums where preloaded prior to carrier picking up trailer. Driver received trailer and inspected with no apparent leaks at that time. Driver then proceeded as instructed by shipper. At safety inspection driver noted leak from trailer and notified response numbers and company officials. First Strike Envro was notified and proceeded to the spill site. They inspected trailer and doned appropriate safety equipment then inspected inside trailer and indentified the cause ans substance of the leak. They then offloaded other drums to isolate leaker. Leaker was then transfer to another drum and secured. The area and the trailer was then decontaminated of any substance. Driver was then released.

column168: Driver was driving South on Hwy 18 south of Bolivar, TN when a car pulled out in front of him.  Due to heavy braking, the load shifted causing the straps to break and allowed a tank containing ~25 gallons of Hypochlorite Solution to fall off onto the roadside.  The tank split on impact and approximately 25 (less than RQ) of the product spilled.  Local fire department and state police arrived at the scene.  The Fire Dept. diulted the spill with water and Royster-Clark employees used AGSORB to soak up remaining water.  A backhoe was then used to remove contaminated soil along side the road and contaminated soil was then hauled to the local county landfill upon Fire Chief's and State Police approval.  State Police inspected the truck and trailer at the scene and completed a Roadside Inspection report citing two load securement violations.  No other mechanical or drive deficiences were noted.
column169: New straps will be purchased to re-enforce side rails on the trailer.  Inspection and maintenance procedures for load securement reviewed with all applicable employees.

column168: ON JUNE 2,2006 KAUAI COMMERCIAL CO (KCC) TRANSPORTED A SEALED INTERMODAL CONTAINER (CONTAINER # PONU 741238 FOR YELLOW FREIGHT FROM THE YOUNG BROTHERS/HORIZON LINES YARD AT NAWILIWILI HARBOR TO THE KCC LOADING DOCK.  UPON UNSEALING AND OPENING THE CONTAINER DOORS, KCC DISCOVERED TWO PORTABLE TANKS MARKED AND LABELED AS CONTAINING METHYLTRICHLOROSILANE.  THE INTERMODAL CONTAINER HAD NOT BEEN PLACARDED AND NO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL SHIPPING PAPER HAD BEEN PROVIDED FOR THE SHIPMENT, KCC NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER OF THE UNDECLARED SHIPMENT. BECAUSE THE SHIPMENT WAS RECEIVED ON FRIDAY AFTERNOON, THE STILL UNDECLARED SHIPMENT WAS THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE FACILITY That normally receives this chemical for offloading and safe storage over the weekend (company policy prohibits storage of this chemical at KCC warehouse for 24 hours) The following Monday, KCC returned to the facility, placarded the shipment, and transported it under a hazardous materials shipping paper back to Nawiliwili harbor for return to shipper on Oahu.

column168: The cargo and billing dangerous goods declaration was tendered to Horizon Lines, the steamship carrier, on 6/21/06 around 15:17.  The original billing only listed one hazmat item which was 3 pails of UN3264 a class 8 corrosive.  The shipper phoned Horizon Lines the following day and faxed corrected documents which included an additional 24 cargons of class 3 UN1133 adhesives on 6/22/06 at 11:54.  The corrected documentation was received after the cargo had been loaded on the cargo vessel and sailed the port.
column169: The customers should have a check and balance to ensure that cargo loaded is billed correctly.  I think that if there was a 24 hour advance manifesting requirement similar to the international business, it would allow customers to reconcile their records prior to the cargo being stowed and lifted to the ocean vessel.  A twenty four hour advance cargo and shipping paper receipt will allow more time for cargo audits prior to lifting to the vessel.

column168: The shipment of household goods was booked and moved rail out of Kentucky to Tacoma for lifting to a Horizon Lines ocean vessel for shipment to Alaska.  The container was inspected at the port in Tacoma as part of our tariff agreement.  The inspector found 2 Polaris ATV gasoline powered vehicles.  Both units had 1/4th tank of fuel.  There was also one box of Tide laundry detergent leaking from the container.  The two vehicles should have been shipped under UN3166, Vehicles, Flammable Liquid Powered, 9.  The shipper was contacted about the descrepency to obtain updated documentation to reflect the shipment.  The warning sign was added to the doors of the container.
column169: Household goods and Personally Owned Vehicles shipped by private citizens cause problems in transportation due to the fact that many of the shippers are private citizens and are not required to be trained.  Our booking departments provide general knowledge and guidance on the shipment but there is no guarantee that the orrerer will comply.  Shipments of this type must routinely be audited prior to lifting to a ocean vessel.

Carrier driver had performed the discharge of product from an IBC on his trailer (utilizing DOT SP-12412)to the customers storage tank.He then attached compressed air to a "blow down fitting" to clear the 2" hose of residual product. As he was inside of the trailer (approx 8ft), he was unable to have a line of sight to the customer tank.An employee of the customer quickly notified the driver that the 2" hose had come out of the tank and sprayed another employee with phosphoric acid 75% on his right side, including some in his eye.The customers other employee's in the area immediately responded to bring the effected employee to a safety shower. The driver immediately shut off the air and assisted the exposed employee while he was in the safety shower (keeping him there for 20+minutes). After employee was rinsed sufficiently, the customers Operations Manager took him to a local clinic for treatment. The local clinic recommended that he should see an eye specialist. The employee returned to work 2-3hrs later to gather his belongings and was taken to a eye specialist, treated and released home. Employee returned to work the next morning at full duty status with only minor eye irritation.     The remaining product that had sprayed the transfer area was completely contained and cleaned up in-house. All residual material was flushed to the neutralization pit for treatment prior to discharge. The transfer area where the customer tank is stationed is completely bermed and contained. Estimated amount of product spilled was 8 gallons.
column169: Customer and Carrier Incident Investigation found the following corrective actions necessary for a safe off loading operation.  1. Driver did not secure the discharge hose to tank. Corrective Action: Carrier has installed camlock fittings to tank and provided driver with securement training.  2. Customer did not provide 2nd man at the tank to assist carrier driver. This was an agreed to procedure with the customer from the carrier at the initial managers delivery survey. Corrective Action: Customer will ALWAYS provide a 2nd man, fully suited in proper corrosive PPE prior to carrier discharging product. Carrier drivers have been instructed to discontinue the transfer process if the customers employee leaves the transfer area.

column168: The customers line began leaking during the unload process where a 2" fitting attached to the plastic fill line. There was a bucket underneath this connection as a precautionary measure before the unload began but the product missed the bucket and fell to the ground.  The product probably leaked for a few minutes before it was discovered. The unloading was stopped and the customer tightened the fitting to the fill line and the unlaoding process resumed without any further incidents.
column169: The customer fill line and connection were loose which was the root cause of the leak. This was repaired while the driver waited and then the unload was completed. The driver and customer had put buckets under all connections as a precaution prior to beginning the unload unfortunately the product leaked down and missed the bucket. The product spill was cleaned up by the consignee using sand. The consignee mentioned to our driver that he will check all connections prior to delivery on future loads to make sure everything is tight.

column168: The driver was operating the product pump and the unloader at the consignee was working the drumming nozzle as they unloaded the product from the tank trailer into totes.  The unloader did not shut off the drumming nozzle quickly enough on one of the totes as it filled up causing an overflow of 4 liquid gallons.
column169: Operator error by the consignee who was working the drumming nozzle resulted in the spill.  Recommendations would be for our driver to run his product pump at a slower rate and to communicate better with the unloaders as the totes are nearing the full mark to be better prepared to either slow the flow of product down even further or to shut off the flow up product using the product pump to help prevent future incidents such as this.

At approximately 7:00 am on June 9, 2006 a spill ocured in the trailer that was being backed up to an unloading dock at a fully contained yard of Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc, facility located at 2815 Old Greenbrier Pike, Greenbrier, TN.  The vehicle was being backed into a containment dike in order for the load to be transfered to an awaiting trailer.  Upon opening the rear compartment of the vehicle, the dock personnel noticed a tipped over 55 gallon container leaking material onto the trailer floor.    They immediately notified their supervisor of the incident, retrieved the shipping papers to review the contents of the vehicle.  It was determined that this shipment only contained materials from Toray Fluorofibers America Inc, picked up the day before.  In order to destribute the weight evenly over the  length of the trailer, the cargo was split into two distinct areas of the trailer.  The material was  secured by utilizing numerous load locking devises.  During the backing up operation, the vehicle went over a containment barrier, and the resulting movement to the trailer caused one of  the load bracing devices to dislodge and one 55 gallon drum containing Class 8 corrosive material to tip over and fall off a pallet.  The fall of the drum resulted in a failure of a closing device which resulted in a loss of that drum's content.      After the verification of the material, an in-house clean up crew donned appropriate personal protective equipment and entered the material hauling portion of the vehicle.  The drum was uprighted and the spilled liquid was cleaned up utilizing compatible absorbent material.  All of the absorbent material used to clean up the spill was collected and placed into appropriate drums for disposal at a fully licensed waste management facility.  Approximately 50 gallons of material was spilled inside the transport vehicle, about one quart of material seeped through the floor boards of the trailer onto a fully contained concreet dike, which was also cleaned up utilizing appropriate methods.  The time frame from the initial notice of the spill until the drum was uprighted and the spill cleaned up was approximately 2 to 3 hours.  Please note that during the release and until the clean up operation was complete, the vehicle was parked in a fully contained concrete dike.  All of the spilled material was contained and no offfsite impact occurred .
column169: Our investigation determined that the cause of the incident was impropper load securement and subsiquent movement over the berm of the containment.  The individual responsible for loading and securing this load will receive additional training on proper cargo securement.  In addition the load securement devices used during this incident will be reviewed for defects and replaced if necessary.  The company policy regarding splitting the cargo will be reviewed for effectiveness and amended as needed to mitigate another occurrence of such incident.

column168: Driver had completed unloading product from cargo tank to customer storage tank.  He thought the unloader at the plant had closed the check valve on the fill line to the customers tank.  It looked like it was in the closed position when, in fact, it was not closed.  Driver proceeded to disconnect his hose from the fill line and once he disconnected a surge of product came back out of the fill line onto him.  Customer hosed him down immediately and put him in a shower for 15 minutes.  He was taken to hospital to be examined.  He was treated and released.
column169: Driver should have followed procedure and checked customer valve before disconnecting.  When in doubt if it was closed or not, he should have had the unloader verify if it was open or closed.  Driver was also not wearing the prescribed PPE for this product.  This problem is being addressed at our annual training this month.

column168: Trailers are loaded in plant, aired up to 25psi and observed for 15 minutes to dertermine if there is any loss of pressure.  If there is no drop in air pressure it is sealed and deemed ready for shipment.  The driver is not to open domes after they are sealed and pressured checked.  The driver can then visually observe the gasket after unload is complete and some of the domes are opened up to rinse out any residue.  Rear dome gasket started leaking very slowly after tank was pumped liquid full and pressured up to circulate customer water solution through cargo tank during blending process.  Trailer dome gaskets passed the air pressure test performed by loading operator.
column169: The manager had our mechanic inspect the domes of each cargo tank in terminal parking area and found numerous questionable gaskets.  Replacement gaskets are being ordered and installed as quickly as possible.  Based on results of this inspection, Sentinel will initiate a periodic dome gasket check on the cargo tanks.  The manager will train all drivers to insure each one has the ability to recognize a serviceable gasket versus one that has started to deteriorate and needs to be replaced to prevent a possible problem  The employees of the Carlin terminal will develop a system to insure that any questionable gasket noted by driver after unloading are reported so they can be repaired-replaced prior to reloading of the trailer.    We are requesting a technical review of gasket material currently specified to determine if it is still the best choice for this application with the maximum durability.  We are also requesting a joint review of the current procedure to pressure test the cargo tanks after loading to determine if the air pressure limits and the observation time is adequate.  Review could also explore any newer technologies that could help detect small air leaks that might be missed in current process but would indicate a likely leak after the cargo tank is filled liquid full and pressurized at customer site.

CAUSE CODE:  200  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) * (2=0) =60

column168: At 06:OOam the driver of the truck and tanker was making a left hand turn from East bound State Route 90 to Hatfield Road. Halfway through the turn the tanker rolled onto its side and slid approximately 20 feet. The truck and tanker then struck a curb and sidewalk flipping almost completely on its back. The tank was torn on the top rail and shoulder of the driver’s side approximately 10 feet from the front of the trailer. Also, the dome lids for compartment 1, 2 and 3 were partially open and the dome lid for compartment 4 was all the way open. The tear was approximately 1 square foot in size. The transportation manager and dispatcher were notified at approximately 9:30am by the driver. When we were notified we called the law enforcement agency in charge (the Arizona Department of Public Safety), our insurance company, our hazmat coordination company, upper management, a clean up contractor, the National Response Center and the Arizona Department of Environmental Quality. The product leaked from the time of the accident until approximately 2:30pm (8 1/2 hours) under the supervision of the local fire department. Nothing was done to mitigate the release, per the fire department, however, dirt was placed in several locations to stem the flow down the drainage.

FCO(Rome, Italy) cargo accepted a shipment tendered as Electrical Equipment. The shipment consisted of 2 shrink-wrapped skids. One was a single banded piece and the other consisted of 15 loose boxes. The shipment traveled on DL flight 149/27MAY06 to JFK then connected via truck to CLE. As agent in CLE was preparing to release shipment to customer they noticed Class 3, Flammable Liquid labels on several packages. The agent refused to release shipment and notified their supervisor. CLE notified DL's Corporate DG group (DGMG) via our internal notification system. DGMG advised CLE to quarantine the shipment and notify the local FAA Regional Office. FAA Special Agent Stevens visited CLE on June 5, 2006 to review the shipment, take pictures, and advised CLE they would handle moving forward. Once Agent Stevens completed the investigation the shipment was authorised for release. It has come to the attention of DGMG that the Flammable Liquid labels may have been added to the shipment in an attempt to get the shipper in trouble. This has not yet been confirmed, but is being investigated by Delta Air Lines.
column169: It is believed that the shipment was not a hazardous material and that the labels were placed on the package after tender to DL for transportation. As stated earlier, it is believed that another shipper or someone in conjunction with transport of this shipment placed the labels on the packages. Delta is conducting an internal investigiation into the event. This report was delayed awaiting our investigation into the shipment. the investigation has not yet been concluded and we did not want to further delay the report to DOT.

column168: FREIGHT HANDLER WENT INTO TRAILER HE SAID IT WAS TOO DARK HE HIT 1 BLUE METAL ABOUT 2 INCH FROM THE BOTTOM.  LIGHTS ON FORKLIFT WERE WORKING FINE.  AS SOON AS THE DRUM WAS PUNTURE THEY STOP IT FROM LEAKING.  ABOUT 4 TO 5 GALLONS LEAKED OUT.
column169: THE FREIGHT HANDLER WILL BE TAKEN OFF A LIFT FOR 2-4 WEEKS. GO THROUGH RETRAINING (YOU ALWAYS COME TO A COMPLETE STOP BEFORE ENTERING A PALLET) ON FORKLIFT MODELUAR.  EVERY TRAILER LIGHT WAS WORKING AND PM ON EVERY IS DONE BEFORE SHIFT.

File 06-249 DOT       Shipper-Superior Moble Medics      AWB#-ATL 31372934246 DOE    On 06/10/2006 at 0303, a leaking shipment was reported in C building of our main sort facility, located at ABX air, Inc.  Spill technician Michael Oliver donned proper presonal protective equipment and responded.  Upon arrival, he found a lab pack with visible signs of leakage on the outer package.  He removed the package from the area and began his investigation.  Upon this investigation, he found this package to contain 2x8 oz and 1x4 oz plastic bottles of diagnostic specimens.  Due to a loose closure on the 4 oz bottle, 2 oz of the product was lost.  This shipment arrived into Wilmington via flight #381, N795AX    This shipment was declared a diagnostic specimen.    Clear of Scene: 0316    There are pictures on file in the hazmat office in Wilmington, Ohio.

During the loading of a box trailer, an IBC fell off the forklift forks and into the trailer.  The IBC fell when the forklift was driving over the dock plate that was at a higher elevation than the trailer floor.  Upon impact, the IBC lid cracked and phosphoric acid ran out of container into trailer floor and dock area. Site employees shut and sealed nearby drains and controlled the release with spill pillows.  All spilled material was picked up and entire area flushed and neutralized.
column169: Operating procedures have been modified to ensure the trailer axles are slid all the way back when trailer is spotted for loading.  This serves to stabilize the rear of trailer.

WITH THE TYPE OF HAZMATS LOADED ON THE TRAILER, I IMMEDIATELY TOLD THE DRIVER TO DROP THE TRAILER AND CONTAIN THE LEAK ON THE GROUND WITH SOME ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  AFTER CLEAN-UP WAS DONE, WE REALIZED THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS DUE TO MULTIPLE LIDS BEING LOOSE AND A CRACK AROUND THE LID IN THE METAL.

column168: WHILE DOCK ASSOCIATE WAS ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD TOTE BIN FROM OUR TRAILER THE TOTE BIN CAN WAS LODGED AGAINST ANOTHER TOTE BIN AND WHEN DOCK ASSOCIATE TRIED TO PULL THE TOTE BIN OUT OF THE TRAILER USING THE FORKLIFT.  THE CAP ON THE TOTE BIN POPPED OFF CAUSING THE LIQUID TO LEAK FROM THE TOTE BIN.  DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 1.5 MINUTES.  THE TOTE BIN WAS TURNED ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE.
column169: ASSOCIATE HAS BEEN COUNCELED AND WILL VIEW VIDEO ON PROPER HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AS WELL AS FORKLIFT SAFETY AND PROPER USE OF FORKLIFT.  ASSOCIATE WILL ALSO BE RECERTIFIED FOR OPERATING FORKLIFT.

Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver arrived at unloading site to deliver a load of low sulfur diesel.  At this location, the customer's pump is used to offload the product into their tank.  The customer signed FRTL's product integrity form indicating the entire load would fit within 90% capacity.  After the 2nd compartment, the FRTL driver heard a beeping noice and informed the customer.  Approximately 50 gallons of diesel fuel spilled onto the concrete pad and spilled onto the dirt.  Sunnypoint Fire Department responded to the scene.  The customer accepted full responsibility for the incident and handled cleanup.  Customer determined that their tank readings were incorrect.
column169: Customer must keep better track of their remaining inventory in tank so they will have accurate numbers and know when their tank will hold a load of fuel within 90% maximum capacity.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines driver arrived at unloading facility and miscalculated the underground tank capacity.  He did not account for the 90% maximum fill capacity per company policy.  While dropping the 2nd compartment into tank #1, driver stated that tank 1 started "boiling up and would not stop".  Driver immediately stopped the flow of product from the trailer and blocked off the area with the help of the store's assistant manager.  Cat litter was put down to help contain and soak up the product, and FRTL maintenance personnel responded and began clean-up.  Estimated 15 gallons spilled.  All was contained on concrete and did not enter any storm drains or soil.
column169: Re-enforce proper procedures with driver.

Drum was sitting on dock waiting to be loaded.  It was surrounded by empty pallets for protection.  Dock worker was making u-turn on dock and the end of his fork blade punctured small hole in bottom portion of drum.  Spill was contained immediately and drum held in haz mat bay for disposition from shipper.  Spill was cleaned up with neutralizing agent.  Drum and spent agent was disposed of via environmental contractor.
column169: Dock worker issued corrective action and remedial forklift training.  Staging practices reviewed at facility to better protect freight.  Shipment was packaged adequately for transport as received from manufacturer.

column168: INTERMODAL TANK CONTAINER EXFU 380256 REPORTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM ITS BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) IN THE BNSF INTERMODAL PARKING LOT.  EXFU 380256 WAS IMMEDIATELY MOVED TO CONTAINMENT AREA.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDER REPORTED THE BOV HANDLE APPEARED IN THE CLOSED POSITION WITH SEAL INTACT.  THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS FOUND TO BE MORE THAN 3 FULL TURNS FROM BEING TOOL TIGHT AND THE RESPONDER TOOL TIGHTENED THE BOC.  THE BOV HANDLE WAS MANIPULATED TO ENSURE THE VALVE WAS FULLY CLOSED. AFTER THESE SECUREMENT EFFORTS WERE COMPLETED, THE DRIPPING STOPPED.  ALL SPILLAGE EVAPORATED.  RESPONSE CONCLUDED BY 1600 HRS.  CDT, 6/01/2006.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPERS PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE TOTAL SECUREMENT AND MECHANICAL FITNESS OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While exiting the Gilford Rail Terminal in N. Billerica, Massachusetts, a leak was discovered from the cargo tanker.  Apparently, a valve was left open on the tank, which resulted in the release of approximately 19 gallons of ferric chloride.  Originally, the release was reported to have involved approximately 80 gallons of free product.  However, after further inspection of the tanker, it was determined that approximately 19 gallons of ferric chloride were released.  The ferric chloride released to the asphalt surface within the roadway.  No soil or waters of the state were affected by the release.  The Massachusetts Department of Public Works responded to contain the free product with the application of sand to the affected roadway.  The N. Billerica Fire Department also responded and applied lime to neutralize the free product.  TMC Services, Inc. of Bellingham, Massachusetts was dispatched to perform the remainder of cleanup.  TMC Services, Inc. recovered the spent sand and neutralized product, which was containerized into eighteen (18) 55-gallon drums.  Disposal was coordinated per local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to an open valve on the cargo tanker, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  The carrier will continue to reinforce safe handling procedures and safety guidelines to all personnel.

THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL SIX-FOUR LITRE METAL CANS, EACH WITH FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABELS AND DANGEROUS GOODS MARKINGS.  WE SUBSEQUENTLY LEARNED THAT IT WAS ONE OF A 34 PIECE SHIPMENT.  THE FEDEX JFK RAMP WAS NOTIFIED AND THE OTHER 33 BOXES WERE RECOVERED FROM THE AIRCRAFT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS, EMERGENCY RESPONSE, NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED.  I SPOKE TO SA STEVEN JOSEPH & THEN SA JOHN BOGLE.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.
THE PACKAGE CONTAINED AND AIRCRAFT PART THAT LEAKED FUEL THE PART WAS REPACKED AND RETURNED.

DURING THAT TIME THE BOX BEGAN TO SIFT OUT THE CONTENTS (POWDER).  THE BOX WAS OPENED TO REVEAL AN MSDS.  IT WAS ON THE MSDS THAT INDICATED THAT IT WAS REGULATED BY DOT.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS EMERGENCY RESPONSE NOR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SEC FO MGR CARL MOSBY.  THE FREIGHT WAS HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.

column42: EXPLOSIVE, BLASTING, TYPE B OR EXPLOSIVE, AGENT BLASTING, TYPE B
column168: Lynden Transport, Inc. was hired to move a shipper load and count, sealed van of explosives to an awaiting cargo plane for transport to final destination.  While using a forklift to transfer the material from the van to the cargo plane a Lynden Air cargo employee noticed a bag had been punctured by the forks when entering the pallet.    Austin Powder was contacted to repair the punctured bag and re-palletize the shipment onto a pallet with a cardboard pallet liner.  The liner prevent the bags from settling through the gaps in the pallet.  Austin Powder cleaned up the spill material.  Loading resumed immediately after repair of the bag.
column169: This incident could have been prevented by using cardboard pallet liners or solid top pallets to prevent the bags from settling through the pallet gaps.  Any future shipments of this product will be loaded onto the proper type of pallet.  The shipper will train their employee on the new requirement.

column168: The box was found wet and emitting a very strong odor.  The box was placed in a salvage bag and opened.  We found two plastic 4 liter (1gallon) bottles, one of which had a pinhole leak.  The screw on caps had no positive closure as required by ICAO 1.1.4.  There was no barrier bag, absorbent material as required in ICAO 1.1.10.1(b).  The cushioning material was bubble wrap.   I called the shipper and requested training records & package test results.  The shipper denied my request.  The FAA was notified, I spoke to SA Bryan Buchanan.  The freight was held for an FAA inspection, which has been accomplished.  The freight is waiting on a disposition.

This shipment was found to be leaking in theFedEx warehouse.  Standard spill cleanup procedures were followed.  This was a combination package (fiberboard outer, plastic inner).  There was a cardboard divider with 4 sections-the two plastic bottles were in two of the sections with bubble wrap in the two voided sections.  There was no absorbent material and no leak proof liner.  Since this was a hazard class 3, packing group II, with a plastic inner receptacle, CAO per IATA 5.1.2.12.2 and Table 5.0.B.  Since these two error cannot be inspected during initial inspection they are hidden packaging errors.  FAA agent Christine Osborne was notified.  The shipment was held pending FAA investigation.

column169: ON THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY(KCSR), SHIPPERS ARE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED OF ALL HAZMAT RELEASES.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELEASES(AKA PACKAGE OR CLOSURE DEFECTS), WHERE POSSIBLE, SHIPPERS (RESPONSIBLE PARTY) ARE REQUESTED TO RESPOND, REPAIR, AND REMEDIATE.  BY IMMEDIATELY INVOLVING THE SHIPPER, IN-DEPTH KNOWLEDGE OF THE RELEASE CAUSE IS GAINED BY THE SAME ORGANIZATION THAT CAN IMPLEMENT PROCESS CHANGES TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.  AFTER EACH NAR INCIDENT, KCSR PROVIDES OUTREACH TO THE SHIPPER TO HELP INVESTIGATE ROOT-CAUSE FACTORS FOR CORRECTION.  FOR NON-ACCIDENT RELATED RELEASES,THE SHIPPER SHOULD BE CONTACTED DIRECTLY FOR DETAILS ASSOCIATED WITH ACTIONS TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT THE SERVICE CENTER AND WAS PLACED IN A STORAGE TRAILER FOR LATER DELIVER.  THE SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF 2 CARTONS ON A PALLET.  IT APPEARS THAT WHEN THE PALLET WAS LOADED ON THE STORAGE TRAILER IT WAS PUSHED FORWARD INTO ANOTHER SKID THAT CONTAINED A DOCK PLATE WITH A SHARP METAL EDGE.  THE SKID CONTAINING THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PUSHED INTO THE SHARP EDGE, IN TURN PUNCTURING THE CARTON AND THEN ONE OF THE METAL CANS THAT ACTUALLY CONTAINED THE PRODUCT.  THE PUNCTURE WAS 3" LONG. THE PUNCTURE WAS APPROXIMATELY 25% OF THE HEIGHT OF THE CAN DOWN FROM its TOP.  THE TOP QUARTER OR APPROXIMATELY A QUART OF THE PRODUCT PROCEEDED TO LEAK OUT.  THIS WAS NOT DISCOVERED AT THE TIME OF LOADING BUT RATHER THE NEXT DAY WHEN THE SHIPMENT WAS UNLOADED FROM THE TRAILER.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT THAT HAD NOT ALREADY DRIED WAS CAPTURED USING AN ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE USED ABSORBENT ALONG WITH THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE CAN WAS PLACED IN A SALVAGE PAIL FOR DISPOSAL.
column169: ALL DOCK WORKERS AT THE FACILITY WILL BE REMINDED OF OUR LOADING RULES FOR HAZMAT THAT IS ALREADY IN PLACE.  ANY SKID OF HAZMAT- DRUMS, PAILS, BAGS, OR CARTONS MUST BE SURROUNDED ON ALL SIDES BY APPROPRIATE DUNNAGE WHETHER LOADED IN A TRAILER FOR TRANSIT OR STORAGE.   LOADS WILL BE INSPECTED FOR COMPLIANCE AND APPROPRIATE DISCIPLINE MEETED OUT FOR NON-COMPLIANCE.

column168: AFTER RAIL INERCHANGE FROM BNSF TO APA(APACHE RAILWAY CO.), THE APA REJECTED GATX22457 DUE TO DRIED PRODUCT RESIDUE ON ITS SIDE SHELL.  INSPECTION OF GATX 22457 BY A BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS RESPONDER INDICATED THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE/DEVICE (PRD) AHD EXPELLED PRODUCT AT SOME POINT IN TIME.  THE PRODUCT OUTAGE WAS DEMED APPROPRIATE, AS IT MEASURED AT 18 INCHES.  THEREFORE, AN OVERFILLED CONDITION WAS NOT A FACTOR IN THIS PRODUCT RELEASE.  THE PROBABLE CAUSE WAS LIKELY FROM HYDRAULIC PRESSURE SURGES DURING RAIL MOVEMENT THAT FORCED THE LIQUID COMMODITY FROM THE PRD VENT ORIFICE.  ON 6/15/2006, A BNSF CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED AND WIPED THE SPILLAGE OFF OF GATX 22457'S SHELL.  CONTRACTOR RESPONSE CONCLUDED BY 2020 HRS. MDT, 6/15/2006. NO PRODUCT IMPACTED THE GROUND.

column168: BNSF CARMEN INSPECTING RAILCARS IN RAILYARD, REPORTED PRODUCT ODOR EMANATING FROM TILX 190167 THAT WAS STANDING ON THE BNSF INTERCHANGE TRACT AWAITING PHYSICAL DELIVERY TO THE CPRS(CP RAIL SYSTEM).  A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER THAT WAS IN THE AREA PERFORMING ENVIRONMENTAL AUDITS INSPECTED TILX 190167 FINDING 4 OF 6 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS NOT TOOL TIGHT.  RESPONDER TOOL TIGHTENED THE LOOSE SECUREMENT BOLTS.  RESPONDER ALSO REPORTED THAT A FRESH PRODUCT STAIN WAS HALF WAY DOWN THE TANK CAR SHELL AND WAS EVAPORATING.  NO PRODUCT IMPACTED THE GROUND.  THE LOCAL FD ALSO RESPONDED.  A BNSF MECHANICAL/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER ARRIVED AND REINSPECTED TILX 190167.  THIS RESPONDER OPENED THE MANWAY LIB AND FOUND THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISALIGHNED.  THE PRODUCT OUTAGE MEASURED 18 INCHES AND WAS DEEMED APPROPRIATE.  RESPONDER REPOSITIONED THE MANWAY GASKET AND RESECURED THE MANWAY LID BY PROPERLY TOOL TIGHENING ALL SIX MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS.  NO FURTHER PRODUCT LEAKAGE OR ODOR WAS DETECTED AFTER SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED AT 1445 HRS.  CDT 6/21/2006.

column168: BNSF MECHANICAL PERSONNEL REPORTED UTLX 200536 SPLASHED PRODUCT ONTO ITS SIDE SHELL DURING NORMAL SWITCHING MOVEMENT IN THE RAILYARD.  A BNSF CONTRACT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL/ENVIONMENTAL RESPONDER NEARBY WAS SUMMONED TO INVESTIGATE AND INSPECT UTLX 200536.  RESPONDER DETERMINED THAT PRODUCT WAS EXPELLED FROM THE CONTINOUS VENT ORIFICE ATOP UTLX 200536.  THE BREATHABLE GORTEX MEMBRANCE OR DIAPHRAGM (USED FOR OXYGEN VENTING) WITHIN THE ONTINOUS VENT WAS COMPROMISED.  THIS MEMBRANCE HAD SEVERAL LARGE HOLES IN THE MATERIAL WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  THE MEMBRANE PUNCTURES WERE CAUSED BY AN OVER PRESSURE EVENT.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THEY IMMEDIATELY SENT A REPLACEMENT MEMBRANCE RING ASSEMBLY TO INSTALL IN UTLX 200536.  INSTALLATION WAS COMPLETED BY 1630 HRS.  CDT, 6/20/2006.  SPILLAGE WAS DILUTED BY HEAVY RAINFALL THAT WAS OCCURING AT THIS TIME.  NO PRODUCT IMPACTED THE GROUND.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: BNSF MECHANICAL RAILCAR INSPECTORS IN THE RAILYARD REPORTED BRSX 9637 WAS HISSING AND VENTING PRODUCT VAPORS VIA THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE(PRD) ATOP THE TANK CAR.  AMBIENT TEMPERATURES AT THIS TIME WERE OVER 100 DEGREES F.  BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND LIQUID PRODUCT ESCAPING VIA THE PRD AND PRODUCT WAS IMMEDIATELY TRANSFORMING INTO VAPOR.  THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS UTILIZED TO DETERMINE THAT THE TANK CAR WAS FULL WITH NO DISCERNABLE PRODUCT OUTAGE.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO OFF-LOAD EXCESS PRODUCT INTO TANKER TRUCKS.  BRSX 9637 WAS ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD AT A LOCATION THAT WAS READILY ACCESSIBLE FOR PRODUCT TRANSFER.  AT 0830 HRS. PDT 6/24/2006, THE TANKER TRUCK ARRIVED AND PRODUCT REDUCTION WAS COMPLETED TWO HOURS LATER AT 1030 HRS PDT WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  AFTERWARDS, BRSX 9637 WAS MONITORED AND NO FURTHER PRODUCT VENTING WAS OBSERVED.  BRSX 9637 WAS THEN RELEASED TO PROCEED TO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: On Sunday June 18, 2006, CVG cargo received a truck of freight from ORD for international export. On the truck was AWB 006-4963-1562, 22 pieces to AMS. There shipment consisted of 12 skids, 8 boxes, and 1 crate. CVG cargo received 21 of 22 pieces and signed off the truck as being 1 piece short. Shortly after arrival, ATS Supervisor Roy DAvis in CVG, alerted CVG cargo of the undeclared DG finding. AS ATS, DL's cargo handler in CVG, were building pallets of the freight, which had arrived shrink-wrapped, Roy noticed a small corner of an exposed hazardous material (Flammable Liquid) label. He brought this to the attention of a DL supervisor and they began the internal notification process. Also on hand at the time of the finding was USCBP Inspector Steven Stahl, who confirmed the presence of the hazard labels and advised notification to the FAA. The packages were turned inwards and stacked against each other so the labels were not visible at the time of acceptance in ORD. Also, there was no DG paperwork present for the shipment. The shipment was quarantined and CVG notified DL's Corporate DG group (DGMG) via our internal notification system. DGMG advised CVG to quarantine the shipment and notify the local FAA Regional Office. The local Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) office in Cincinnati, Ohio has been notified and has inspected the shipment. The shipment consisted of 22 pieces, of which 21 are in CVG, with the last piece shown as Found Cargo in MXP. The question as to how one piece ended up in MXP is being investigated internally by Delta Air Lines.
column169: The shipment appeared to have been prepared as ORM-D, a class of material not allowed by Delta. Delta requires shipments to be reclassified as Consumer Commidity for acceptance. The Flammable Liquid labels were what caused identification of this shipment, but probably also not required. Although the shipment moved via truck to CVG, the shipment was accept properly per current security guidlines. Due to the size of the packages and the need to break down the freight, they were identified to contain hazardous materials and were reported as required.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: A service technician was picking up an older model 1000 gallon tank that our customer was no longer using.  He had just loaded the tank onto a single axil 2 wheeled trailer when the release occurred. The gas in the tank may have shifted due to too much weight on the tire. While on the trailer, the tank tipped to its side and bent the external relief valve causing it to vent.  He was not driving.  Tank was at 75% so about 720 gallons dissipated unitl the tank was empty.     There is no evacuation valve on this older model tank. The filler valve on this older model tank did not have a dip tube.  The only way to get the gas out of this older model tank is to tip it on it's side and evacuate it though the filler valve.  Flaring it off wouldn't have been an option without tipping it over either.  Our service technician thought it would be safer to evacuate the tank at our yard instead of at the customer location.  The Ferrellgas yard is approximately 2 miles from the customer location.

Driver loaded Crude oil at a well site in Samckover, Ark. and proceeded to Shreveport, La..  Approx. 1/8 mile before arriving at unload site driver was informed by C.B. radio that he was leaking oil onto the roadway.  Truck was immediately stopped and driver found that an unknown object had struck the bottom of the tank and caused a 1/2 by 1 inch puncture. Driver stopped flow with a rubber glove and called for assistance.  Shreveport F.D. arrived with La. State Police and a catch basin was placed under leak until F.D. was able to plug leak with putty.  An empty CTMV was dispatched to scene and remaining oil was transferred onto it.  An environmental cleanup company was called to scene to pick up contminated material from roadside and taken away for disposal.  Damaged trailer was taken to MTI terminal in Bossier City, La. for repair.
column169: Driver was advised to be cautious of loose objects lying on roadway that might be hit by tires and become a projectile that could cause damage to equipment.

column168: WHILE ENROUTE, ONE RAILCAR WAS DISCOVERED WITH A LEAKING TRAILER ON IT.  THE TRAILER WAS RESPONDED TO BY A CERTIFIED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM.  THE TEAM DETERMINED THAT TWO 55 GALLLON DRUMS HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY HEAVY FREIGHT, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS.  THE RESPONSE TEAM NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL AND CLEANED THE RAILCAR AND TRUCK TRAILER ON A WASH PAD.  THE DAMAGED DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED IN LINED SALVAGE DRUMS AND HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.
column169: HEAVY FREIGHT SHOULD NEVER BE LOADED ON TOP OF OTHER FREIGHT.

DRIVING NORTH OF 183, 3 MILES NORTH OF PUTNAM AT 530 AM. DARK HERD OF CATTLE ON HIGHWAY.  HIT ONE OR MORE-TOOK EVASIVE MEASURES AND TRUCK SKIDDED AND ROLLED 2.5 TIMES. THE LEFT REAR COMPARTMENT HAD A SEAM CRACK APPROXIMATELY 4" LONG.  THE TRUCK WAS PICKED UP WITH IN THE HOUR OF ACCIDENT.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND DIRT DITCH EVACUATED.

The shipper was the Interplastic Corporation at 5019 Hunt Street in Pryor, OK.  The transporter was Landstar Transportation.  The receiver was North American Composites at 3715 North Frontage Road in Lakeland, Florida.    Landstar delivered the shipment to NAC in Lakeland, Florida.  A NAC warehouse worker was unloading the drums from the van trailer of Landstar Transportation with a forklift when he punctured a drum of resin.    Between 20 to 30 gallons of product leaked onto the floor of the van trailer.    NAC personnel cleaned up the spill.    The spill was obviously caused by the forklift operator, who has been retrained on forklift operation and safety.
column169: Retraining of the forklift operator has been completed.

column168: ON JUNE 6, 2006 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:45 PM BUDDY SCHAAT JR. WAS MAKING A DELIVERY OF HYPO TO THE CITY OF POUGHKEEPSIE.  BUDDY WAS TRAVELLING ON RT 94 AND WHEN HE STOPPED AT THE RED LIGHT IN GOSHEN, NY THE RUPTURE DISC BLEW ON OUT TANKER 5109.  BUDDY IMMEDIATELY GOT OUT AND CAPPED THE DISC TO STOP THE LEAK.  DEPUTY SHERIFF A. ROMANOWSKI WAS DRIVING BY AND STOPPED TO SEE WHAT HAD HAPPENED.
column169: BUDDY EXPLAINED WHAT HAD HAPPENED TO THE DEPUTY AND HE HAD BUDDY CALL ME TO ASK WHAT NEEDED TO BE DONE.  WHEN BUDDY CALLED ME I ASKED HOW MUCH BLEACH WAS SPILLED ON THE ROAD WHICH WAS LESS THAN ONE GALLON.  I TOLD BUDDY TO LET THE DEPUTY KNOW THAT WE WERE SENDING CHARLIE MANN OVER TO REPLACE THE RUPTURE DISC AND HELP WITH THE CLEAN UP.  BUDDY THEN TOLD ME THAT THE DEPUTY SAID HE WOULD HAVE THE LOCAL HAZMAT TEAM LEADER COME AND HOSE IN DOWN.  THE HAZMAT TEAM ARRIVED IN MINUTES TO HOSE DOWN THE SPILL ALONG WITH CHARLIE.  DARRYL VANDERMARK THE HAZMAT TEAM CALLED ME TO INFORM THAT THEY WASHED DOWN THE SPILL AND HAD CHARLIE INSTALL THE NEW RUPTURE DISC.  AFTER CHARLIE INSTALLED THE DISC AND THEY CHECKED IT FOR LEAKS WHICH NONE WERE FOUND BUDDY WAS ABLE TO BRING THE TANKER BACK.

column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO THE LOADER. EXPLAIN THE IMPORTANCE OF PROPERLY PROTECTING OUR CUSTOMERS FREIGHT ESPECIALLY WHEN WE ARE MOVING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: During the unloading process the driver discovered that one pallet of material had fallen and hit the side of the trailer wall.  This fall caused five 5-gallon buckets to be crushed and release the contents inside.  Upon this discovery, the driver called for a cleanup crew.  The crew arrived and began off loading the damaged containers of Power Champ Cleaner. The liquid released from the buckets had traveled the length of the trailer and soaked all the pallets.  The soaked pallets were removed and placed onto visqueen to prevent any contamination of the parking lot.  Each 5-gallon buket was de-palletized and placed onto a new, clean pallet.  The 21 soaked pallets were removed and sent for disposal at a FDEP Permitted Solid Waste facility.  All buckets of Power Champ that were not damaged were re-palletized and delivered into Cheney Brothers receiving.  The five damaged buckets were put into one 55-gallon drum for future disposal.  With the truck completely unloaded, granular sorbents were applied to absorb any free liquid left.  This material was swept up and placed into one 55-gallon drum for disposal.  The visqueen and ppe worn by the response team was placed into two 55-gallon drums for disposal.    The entire cleanup from initial notification to job completion took approximately 11 hours.
column169: A recommendation will be made to the shipper to addequately block and brace pallets prior to shipment.  The use of load locks on tall pallets will also be suggested.  This would help to prevent any tipping during transportation.

column168: Our driver had just started loading his bobtail.  He was just leaving the compressor shack where he had turned all valves on to turn the compressor on to start filling. While working out of the compressor shack he heard a pop sound.  He reached in the doorway to shut off the compressor and there were flames.  The compressor is electric and this is how the trucks are loaded.  We suspect the flex connector (a flexible steel braided hose that is reinforced with stainless steel in the piping system)burst because all of the area above was burnt and everything below was not.  There was fire at a pressure gauge on the 30 gallon tank as well.  After arriving on scene, the fire department turned off the valve and stopped the gas from flowing.  The continuing fire stemmed from vapor coming from the piping near the compressor shack and a small grass fire.  This is an industrial park and two nearby companies were evacuated.  We are not sure of the exact number of people evacuated at this time.  Our employee was admitted to Emanuel Hospital Burn Center in Portland, OR and he is still there undergoing treatment for his burn injuries as of today.    We suspect that the cause of ignition was electro static discharge.
column169: We are investigating whether or not electro static discharge can somehow be minimumized.

column168: At approximately 9:30 am EST on Saturday, June 17, 2006, a red solution was observed dripping from the floor of a trailer parked at the Covenant Transport Oklahoma City Terminal. The solution dripped into water puddles on asphalt under the trailer. The driver notified Covenant Transport Risk Management Department that the haz mat cargo (resin solution) was leaking.  An Emergency Response Team, ERS, Inc. was mobilized to the site, arrived at approximately 10:50 am and proceeded to open the trailer. The leak appeared to be coming from one drum at the front of the trailer. Granular sorbents were placed on the spilled resin in the trailer to reduce vapors. The resin and water in the puddles under the trailer were absorbed with sorbents which were placed in a 55-gallon drum.  After off-loading the undamaged drums, the damaged drum was overpacked in a salvage drum.  The drum appeared to have been damaged by a sharp object or impact during loading. The ER Team scraped the resin from the floor of the trailer, removing the majority of the released product; however, an odor remained due to resin trapped within the floor boards. Cleanup activities were completed for the day at approximately 8:00 pm.  Final cleaning of the floor of the trailer was scheduled for Monday, at which time the wood on the floor of the trailer was pressure washed, with the rinseate collected and placed in the drum with previously containerized debris. This was somewhat effective, but did not satisfactorily remove the odor.  After consulting with the manufacturer and Covenant Transport Risk Management, it was decided to remove the impacted floor boards for disposal.  The wood was removed from a 3' x 3' area. The wood was placed in the 55-gallon drum. The underlying metal was wiped down with acetone to remove residual resin. The rags were added to the drum of debris for disposal as hazardous waste, along with the overpacked damaged drum.
THE PAILS WERE DAMAGED DUE TO IMPROPER BLOCKING CAUSING RELEASE OF PRODUCT.

column168: Driver had offloaded part of the load from his cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  He was going to deliver the remaining product into a different storage tank.  As he was setting up, a jack started to fall and as he reached out to grab it with one hand, he accidently grabbed the external valve which had the transport plug in it with the dog ears latched.  When he grabbed it, it unlatched one of the dog ear's and it somehow still had pressure in the cavity which shot the plug off and sprayed out  approximately one quart or less of product on drivers face.  Driver said he did relieve the pressure in the cavity after the first tank so is unsure why there was still pressure in it.  Driver immediately got into an emergency shower until the ambulance arrived.  He was taken to the hospital where he was treated and released.  On-site personnel said the driver just had safety glasses on.
column169: We are taking additional action to stress the importance of wearing the prescribed PPE.  These actions include, but are not limited to, getting a commitment from the drivers as to what PPE they will be wearing when they call in for delivery verification.  We will pay visits to customers to observe deliveries.  Fleet messages go out to remind the drivers the serious consequences of not wearing the proper PPE.

column168: Driver had completed the transfer of product from cargo tank to customer storage tank.  He said he bled the line, disconnected from the trailer and then disconnected from the customer fill line.  When he disconnected from the fill line, there was pressure still in the line that knocked off his hard hat and helmet and some mists got on his face and eyes.  He washed off immediately and didn't report it to anyone because he thought he was okay.  The next morning his eyes were bothering him so he went to the doctor and was treated, released and told to see an eye doctor after the week-end.
column169: Driver received remedial training in wearing the proper PPE.  He had on safety glasses and face shield.  Goggles were required.  Message went out to all the drivers to remind them of the consequences of not wearing the proper PPE.

column168: Driver reported that at shipper, when they loaded the cargo tank they took back washout cap off to put a sensor in.  He saw loader replace cap and tighten it.  Driver checked it again when he did his pretrip when leaving the plant.  At consignee, trailer was at a slant towards the rear.  When customer put nitrogen and pressure to the trailer, some product squirted out of the back washout cap.  They took pressure off trailer, driver repositioned the trailer so that it was level and took washout cap off.  He said the way the trailer was positioned there was product in the neck of the washout cap and the added pressure made it squirt out.  Not sure if it was cross threaded or a problem with the gasket.  There was no sign of leakage from transport.
column169: Need to stress with drivers that just because the washout caps are tight, doesn't necessarily mean they are on properly.

column168: A TANKER TRUCK ARRIVED AT THE FACILITY AT 16:57 HRS REQUESTING 4600 GALLONS OF HRSA.  THE TARE WEIGHT OF THE TRUCK WAS 32,380 POUNDS.  THE LIQUIDS OPERATOR BEGAN LOADING AT 17:20 HRS AT A FLOW AT 120 GPM AT THE START AND LEVELING OFF TO APPROXIMATELY 100 GPM DURING LOADING.  THE LIQUIDS OPERATOR BEGAN VISUAL CHECKS WHEN THE GALLON COUNTER REACHED 4000 GALLONS.  AT THAT TIME THERE APPEARED TO BE ABOUT 18 INCHES OF SPACE LEFT IN THE TANKER.  WHEN THE GALLON COUNTER REACHED 4347 GALLONS, THE LIQUIDS OPERATOR HEARD THE TRUCK OVERFLOW WHILE HE WAS WATCHING THE GALLON COUNTER TO COUNT DOWN TO 4600 GALLONS.  THE LIQUIDS OPERATOR STOPPED THE PUMP, CUT OFF THE VALVES AND CALLED THE LIQUIDS SUPERVISOR.  THE LIQUIDS GENERAL FOREMAN WAS ON SITE AND VERIFIED THAT THE GALLON COUNTER SHOWED 4347 GALLONS.  THIS SAME DRIVER, TRUCK AND TRAILER PICKED UP A LOAD OF HFSA AT 10:00 HRS THAT SAME DAY AND GOT 4597 GALLONS AND WEIGHED OUT UNDER IT'S GROSS LIMIT.  THE LIQUIDS GENERAL FOREMAN REQUESTED THAT THE OPERATING DEPARTMENT INITIATE AN 01 WORK ORDER TO HAVE THE FLOW METER PULLED CHECKED AND REPLACED AS WELL AS REPLACING THE TRANSMITTER.
column169: UNTIL OPERATIONS IS CONFIDENT THAT THE HFSA GALLON COUNTER IS WORKING PROPERLY, THE FOLLOWING PROCEDURE HAS BEEN IMPLEMENTED:  WHEN THE GALLON COUNTER AT THE HFSA LOADOUT REACHES 1,000 GALLONS BELOW THE REQUESTED AMOUNT, THE LIQUIDS OPERATOR WILL CUT OFF THE FLOW AND MEASURE THE LEVEL IN THE TANKER.  THE LIQUIDS OPERATOR WILL REMAIN ON TOP OF THE TRUCK AND HAVE VISUAL CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT UNTIL THE TRUCK IS LOADED.  TO AID IN THE LEVEL MEASUREMENT, THE LIQUID OPERATORS WILL USE A FLASHLIGHT TO INSURE GOOD VISIBILITY.    A HIGH LEVEL SHUT OFF ALARM FOR THIS LOADING OPERATION IS BEING CONSIDERED.

column168: NO PIECE OF EQUIPMENT FAILED.  OUR DRIVER HAD A RELEASE OF PRODUCT WHILE HE WAS DISCONNECTING A HOSE.  THE LOAD WAS SHIPPED IN A COMPARTMENT TRAILER.    WHEN OUR DRIVER FINISHED UNLOADING THE FIRST COMPARTMENT OF DOWTHERM ON HIS TRAILER HE WENT TO DISCONNET THE HOSE FROM THE VALVE ON THE TRAILER.  HE PLACED A BUCKET ON THE GROUND DIRECTLY UNDERNEATH THE VALVE AND WENT TO DISCONNECT THE EARS ON HIS HOSE.  HE FAILED TO RELEASE ALL OF THE PRESSURE IN THE LINE AND THE FORCE OF THE PRODUCT DRAINING INTO THE BUCKET KNOCKED IT OVER CAUSING THE EXCESS PRODUCT TO SPILL ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER TRIED TO RECOVER FROM THE INCIDENT AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE BUT UNFORTUNATELY ABOUT 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.
column169: THE DRIVER WILL BE BROUGHT IN IMMEDIATELY FOR REFRESHER TRAINING.  HE WILL BE SHOWED THE PROPER WAY FOR RELIEVING PRESSURE AND BREAKING DOWN HOSES.  HE WILL ALSO BE COUNSELED ON THE CAUSE AND EFFECT OF THIS INCIDENT AND HE WILL BE RE-TESTED BY OUR OPERATIONS MANAGEMENT TO MAKE SURE HE UNDERSTANDS THAT THIS CAN NEVER HAPPEN AGAIN.  A COPY OF THE EVENT WILL BE DOCUMENTED AND PLACED INTO HIS FILE.  AS A LEARNING TOOL FOR ALL OUR DRIVERS WE WILL DISCUSS THIS EVENT THIS EVENT AT OUR NEXT SAFETY MEETING AND REINFORCE THE IMPPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING OUR UNLOADING PROCEDURES.

PACKAGE ARRIVED AT THE TULSA AIRPORT ON THE 20TH OF JUNE 2006 ON BROWN TAIL 418, IN IGLOO 82257. THE PLANE WAS UNLOADED AND THE IGLOO WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE TULSA HUB.  THE PACKAGE WENT TO D-CAP WHERE IT WAS DETERMINED TO BE DAMAGED BY THE SOUND OF BROKEN GLASS.  THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED FOR INSPECTION AND IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT IT CONTAINED 18 ITEMS THAT WERE FILLED WITH MERCURY, 8 OF WHICH HAD BEEN BROKEN.  AT THAT POINT, THE REPSONSIBLE MANAGEMENT PERSON WAS CALLED ALONG WITH THE DOMICILED P.E. PERSON, DISTRICT ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR, AND THE REGION ENVIRONMENTAL COORDINATOR. THE DECISION WAS MADE TO CONTACT AN OUTSIDE CONTRACTED RESPONDER TO HANDLE THE SPILL.  THE COMPANY THAT WE USE IS EMI.  THEIR PHONE NUMBER IS 405 282- 8510.  EMI SHOWED UP AT THE TULSA BUILDING AT 1130 TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL, AND ANY MERCURY CONTAIMINATED EQUIPMENT, AND ALSO TO RECOVER ANY LEAKED MERCURY.  THE OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR HAS THE PACKAGE IN THEIR POSSESSION ON THEIR PROPERTY.

ON 06/08/2006, DRIVER REPORTED A POSSIBLE LEAK INSIDE THE TRAILER. I INSPECTED DIFFERENT PALLETS AND FOUND 1 WRAPPED PALLET CONTAINING BOTTLES OF CORROSIVE LIQUID. THE TRAILER WAS STRIPPED AND THE PALLET WAS ISOLATED. THERE WERE NO SIGNS OF DAMAGE TO CASES THAT COULD HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY A FORKLIFT OR DEBRIS. IT APPEARS THAT THESE CASES CANNOT SUPPORT EXCESSIVE WEIGHT. 20 CASES WERE EXPOSED TO THE CORROSIVE LIQUID BUT ONLY 5 WERE RUPTURED. THE OTHER 15 CASES WERE DAMAGED BY THE LIQUID. THE SPILL WAS SMALL AND WAS CONTAINED VERY QUICKLY WITH THE USE OF ABSORBENT & CARDBOARD.
column169: IT APPEARS THAT THESE CASES CANNOT SUPPORT WEIGHT. THE SHIPPER SHOULD LIMIT THE AMOUNT OF CASES PER PALLET. THIS IS BECOMING MORE FREQUENT. THEY MIGHT ALSO NEED TO PLACE A SHEET OF CARDBOARD BETWEEN THE PALLET AND THE FREIGHT. THIS WILL PREVENT CASES FROM SLIPPING BETWEEN THE BOARDS.

column168: THE TRUCK WAS LOADED AT MARATHON PETROLEUM TERMINAL IN PADUCAH, KY AT 1545 HRS 6/21/06. #1 COMPT.-2999 GAL GASOLINE, #2-1500 GAL. DIESEL, #3-1000 GAL GASOLINE, #4-2502 GASOLINE.  THIS WAS DONE BY A DAY DRIVER.  HE BROUGHT THE LOAD TO MIDWEST TERMINAL AND PARKED, WHICH WAS ABOUT 1600 HRS.  AT 1800 HRS, THE NIGHT DRIVER LEFT WITH THE LOAD TO DELIVER TO A STATION APPROXIMATELY 20 MILES AWAY.  HE LEFT 5TH ST (MIDWEST) TERMINAL, WENT WEST ONE WAY TO 8TH ST AND CROSSED OVER 1 BLOCK TO MARTIN LUTHER KING EAST (ONE WAY). AT MARTIN LUTHER KING AND 4TH ST THE STREET HAS A 90 DEGREE TURN TO THE RIGHT (THE SPEED LIMIT IS 35 MPH).  ACCORDING TO EYE WITNESSES IT DID NOT APPEAR THE DRIVER WAS SPEEDING.  AS THE DRIVER WAS MAKING THE RIGHT TURN THE UNIT FLIPPED OVER ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE AND CAUGHT FIRE.  THE DRIVER WAS CONSCIOUS AND ALERT AS HE BROKE OUT OF THE PASSENGER SIDE WINDOW AND ESCAPED THE BURNING TRUCK.  ALTHOUGH HE DID SUFFER 2ND AND 3RD DEGREE BURNS ON HIS HANDS AND ARMS.  IT HAS NOT BEEN DETERMINED WHAT FAILED ON THE TANKER.  IT HAD DOUBLE BULKHEADS BETWEEN EACH COMPARTMENT, AND THEY APPEARED TO FUNCTION PROPERLY AS THE FIRE SPREAD FROM FRONT TO THE REAR.
column169: ADDITIONAL TRAINING HAS BEEN DONE TO MID-TERMINAL DRIVERS CONCERNING THE PARTICULAR CURVE WHERE THE ACCIDENT OCCURED.  EVEN THOUGH THE SPEED LIMIT IS 35MPH, THE CURVE WAS POORLY DESIGNED BECAUSE THE BANKING IS ON THE OUTSIDE.  A MORE SAFE SPEED IS PROBABLY 20-25 MPH.

column168: TRAILER 2500612 WAS PUT UP ON THE DOCK FOR BREAK OUT. DOCKWORKER OPENED TRAILER AND SAW THAT 1 PALLET OF MURIATIC ACID HAD FALLEN OVER. PALLET WAS NOT SECURED WITH ROPE OR BLOCKED IN BY OTHER PALLETS. THE BOTTOM BOXES WERE CRUSHED WHEN PALLET FELL OVER. EACH CARTON CONTAINED 2-1 GALLON BOTTLES OF MURIATIC ACID. column168: While moving freight to the section, loader noticed that one drum was leaking from the pallet.  The one drum had a puncture hole with metal protruding.  The drum was laid on its side with loader and second operator assisting.  Dock supervisor contacted the carrier on-call HazMat Dept.  HazMat was informed of situation and advised having trained dock personnel to respond to the incident and having the immediate area evacuated until the cleanup was completed.    Dock called back and advised that the drum was fuming and airborne vapors were bothering personnel.  HazMat advised further evacuation of the area and contacted response crew to the scene.    HazMat notified HMHTTC to respond to the scene with an ETA of one hour.  HazMat Dept also contacted and notified Chemtrec at this time.    Within a half hour, dock called back to inform that the situation had escalated due to dock personnel requesting medical assistance.  Ambulance was called to the scene to transport two personnel to the hospital due to complaints of tightness of chest.  In addition to the ambulance, the local fire department responded.  Their arrival on the scene triggered additional assistance from Delran and the Burlington County HazMat Department.    11:45pm Dock called the HM Dept to inform that response crew is still not at the scene and that the local FD wanted an MSDS for the material.  MSDS was sent and HM Dept Manager decided to go to the scene.    12:00am Dock called the HazMat Department to inform that the response crew still was not at the scene and that the local Burlington County HazMat Dept were assuming Incident Command of the scene.    12:15am HM Dept Manager arrived at the scene as well as the Emergency Response contractor (HMHTTC).  The local FD and HM depts will not allow anyone on or near the dock due to potential exposure to the chemical.    1:00am – 3:00am Local FD and HM Depts controlled response of the incident.  Initial response to the scene involved approximately 21 vehicles including 5 ambulances and 10 fire trucks.  Entry to the dock was performed by two Burlington County HM personnel in Silver Suit Level A Response equipment.  The Incident Commander (IC) progressively reduced response PPE down to Level B by 3:00am.  IC continued to not allow HMHTTC into the scene or on the dock.  Local HM team neutralized spilled product, overpacked drum, and shoveled clean up from the floor into overpacks.    3:40am Dock was allowed to return to operation and moved overpacked drum/cleanup into the hazardous waste area for future disposal.
column169: Cause of the incident was trailer floor repair that punctured bottom edge of the drum.  Drum was overpacked and maintenance department was informed of repair failure.

column168: A BNSF TRAIN OPERATING ON UPRR MAIN TRACK DERAILED 13 RAILCARS INCLUDING SEVEN TANK CARS LADENED WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND RESIDUES OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE CAUSE OF THIS DERAILMENT WAS CONTRIBUTED TO A BROKEN RAIL. GATX 11588 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE AND WAS REPORTED DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY CLOSURE. NEARBY US HIGHWAY 90 WAS PARTIALLY CLOSED DURING THE INITIAL RESPONSE PHASE. AS REPORTED BY HOUSTON F.D. RESPONDING, THEY RETIGHTENED THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS ON GATX 11588 WHICH EBBED THE LEAK TO A SLOWER DRIP BY 1445 HRS. CDT, 6/27. A RECEPTACLE WAS PLACED UNDER THE DRIP AREA TO CATCH SPILLAGE. BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS ALSO RETIGHTENED THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS TO SLOW THE DRIP FURTHER. DURING CLEARING OF THE DERAILED RAIL EQUIPMENT, GATX 11588 WAS OBSERVED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) AREA. THE BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS REPORTED THAT THE BOV EXTENSION WAS SHEARED OFF IN THE DERAILMENT AND THE BOV OPERATING HANDLE WAS BENT. RESPONDERS REMOVED THE BOV HANDLE AND TOOL TIGHTENED THE HANDLE STEM RETAINER NUT WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK FROM THIS SOURCE. RESPONDERS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT THE BOV FLANGE AREA WAS LEAKING AND ALL THE FLANGE BOLTS WERE TOOL TIGHTENED WHICH SLOWED THE LEAK FROM THIS SOURCE. GATX 11588 WAS UPRIGHTED AND A WADING POOL WAS PLACED UNDER THE BOV LEAK TO CATCH FURTHER SPILLAGE. THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN GATX 11588 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANKER TRUCKS FOR DELIVERY BACK TO THE ORIGIN LOADING TERMINAL. TRANSFER OF GATX 11588 WAS COMPLETED BY 1715 HRS. CDT, 6/28/06. AFTERWARDS ON 6/28, GATX 11588 WAS CLEANED AND PURGED OF ALL HAZARDOUS MATERIAL. MOST SPILLAGE READILY EVAPORATED. BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS SAMPLED GROUND IMPACT AREAS AND FURTHER GROUND SOIL REMEDIATION IS PENDING SOIL SAMPLE ANALYSIS.

Freight was shipped as non-regulated freight. Some of the freight was found leaking and the consignee refused the entire shipment. The delivering terminal did not recognize the fact that this freight was hazardous. The delivering terminal was given instructions to return this back to the original sh  ipper in Georgia. This went back to them and they refused it. The freight went back to our Atlanta, GA terminal and they realized the freight was hazmat and got our Safety and Security Department involved on August 4th. The shipper was contacted and there was a discussion about the freight being haz  ardous, it had leaked, the freight was not declared as hazmat, etc. The shipper agreed to accept the damaged freight back so ABF made sure the damaged package(s) was placed into a salvage container. The shipper issued a corrected BOL showing the hazmat description and ABF returned the freight.
column169: Insure proper documentation for hazardous materials on the shipper's part. ABF should have handled the freight properly without damaging it regardless if it was hazmat or not.

column168: Driver was traveling north on Grant County Road S and lost control of the vehicle. After leaving the roadway, the truck rolled 1.75 times, coming to a rest on the drivers side face west. The container, properly secured for normal driving, went through the fiberglass roof of the truck and came to rest at an angle on the ground. Less than 2 gallons (less than 8 lbs. a.i.) spilled out of the vent on top of the tank. Our driver was able to call for immediate assistance. After emergency response teams arrived from Ulysses, crew members were able to set the tank upright, and the Ieakage stopped.    Please note that there was no failure of the tank or fittings, in spite of the fact that response teams estimated the tank may have flown at least 12 feet in the air before coming to rest on the ground.    Most of the containers in tne truck remained in the truck. There was minor spillage of non-regulated materials inside of the truck, mainly from 2.5 gallon plastic containers and some paper bags.    This incident was called into the State Emergency Spill Response Center and National Response Center when we were notified of the accident and that trifluralin had been released, but before we knew if a reportable quantity had been released. It was not until several hours after the incident that we were able to determine (by weight) that a quantity less than the RQ had actually been released.
column169: The accident was a result of driver error, and he was cautioned to drive more carefully in the future. We do not feel that additional training, use of better packaging, or improved operating procedures would help prevent a recurrence.

column168: This release involved a bobtail fuel truck rollover. 911 was called. The  local ambulance, fire dept. and KS Hwy Patrol responded. NRC and EPA were contacted.. Our driver was going north from Cairo to Preston on a county blacktop when he leaned over to answer the radio, lost control and rolled. Although the truck landed on its wheels, the bulk fuel compartment tore off the truck chassis and landed on its side. The stated capacity of the six fuel compartments was 1800 Gal. One compartment was empty, one was full of gas (328G) and the other four were full of diesel fuel (155G). All the compartments remained intact and the lids remained closed. The fuel was pumped off into another Cairo Coop bobtail fuel truck. The only spillage came from the fuel compartments dripping out the vents located on the fuel lids. The ditch was dammed up with dirt and plastic was put in place. A total of 10 gallons of gas and diesel mixture was recovered from this makeshift containment. Based on the maximum amount of fuel that could have been on the fuel truck, a total of another 10 gallons of fuel was spilled in the ditch. After the vehicle was removed, this contaminated dirt was picked up and spread on Cairo Coop’s parking lot. A bag of lawn fertilizer wa mixed in to help the degradation process. The ditch was then back filled with uncontaminated dirt and re—leveled by Cairo Coop the same day of the accident. These remediation procedures were recommended by and reported to employee of  Pratt Co LEPC and employee, KS EPA Region 7 Duty Officer. The bobtail fuel truck was totaled in the accident.

column168: On June 8, 2006 an Univar driver (Rick Patterson) went to 5297 River Road, Cincinnati, Ohio to pick up a trailer of diluted sodium hydroxide that was previously loaded. The driver hooked up to the trailer at approximately 3:30 pm (driver did not perform a pretrip inspection) and then went to the scale and was weighed. The driver noticed some leakage at this time but thought it was from the troughs that are used to hold the unloading hoses as it had rained in previous days. The driver left the loading facility and traveled west on US 50 (River Road) to north on St. Rt. 128 and then turned onto the eastbound ramp to I-74. He pulled over on the eastbound ramp because he noticed a splash and then secured the front dome. The driver then proceded onto his final destination of Univar USA Inc. at 4600 Dues Drive, Cincinnati, Ohio. Upon arrival at Univar the driver went to the trailer wash area and rinsed off the tractor and trailer. Upon pulling into the trailer wash area, he damaged the tractor's exhaust system. The driver then parked the tractor and trailer. The driver reported the exhaust system damage to the dispatcher and then left work for the day. The dispatcher went (now approximately 6:45 p.m.)to check the damage to the tractor and noticed marks on the tractor and trailer like it had been sprayed with acid or caustic. The truck and trailer was still wet from the rinsing. The dispatcher reported his findings to the Traffic Manager and they agreed to follow-up further the following day. Upon further investigation the next morning, the trailer and tractor was noted to have visible signs of sodium hydroxide residue. The domes were checked and the back dome was found to be unsecured. The driver's route was then retraced and there were signs along part of the route of sodium hydroxide spillage. The areas with the largest amount of spillage appeared to be at points where the driver had to come to a stop or make a turn. The two main areas were at the intersection of US 50 and St.R.t 128 and at the turn onto the eastbound I-74 ramp. There was no signs of spillage after the point were the driver stopped to secure the dome. Based on weight tickets from the loading faciltiy and the destination, it was determined that 3000 pounds of sodium hydroxie had been lost. At this point the notifications were made to the NRC and the Ohio EPA. A response contractor was hired to clean up any remaining liquid and absorbents (a local fire department and/or road crew had responded the previous day)in accordance with the Ohio EPA's recommendations.
column169: All drivers will recieve additional training regarding pretrip inspections and reporting of spills.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ON JUNE 2, AT 0615 HOURS, CSX TRANSPORTATION'S YARD CREW WORKING IN ATLANTA, GEORGIA(TILFORD YARD), REPORTED AN UNUSUAL ODOR FROM TANK CAR PLMX30072 (RESIDUE:  LAST CONTAINED AMMONIA, ANHYDROUS). CSX MANAGEMENT IMMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THEIR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN AND THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT NUMBER 06022006043) AND THE SHIPPER, HELENA CHEMICAL WAS INFORMED OF THE NON ACCIDENT RELEASE.  CSX CONTRACTED SWS FIRST RESPONSE TO SECURE THE CONTAINER.  UPON ARRIVAL, SWS REPRESENTATIVES FOUND THE GAUGING DEVICE (SLIP TUBE) NEEDLE VALVE PLUG LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT WITH THE VALVE IN THE OPEN POSITION.  SWS CLOSED THE NEEDLE VALVE AND PROPERLY INSTALLED THE PLUG TO SECURE THE RAILCAR.  APPROXIMATELY TWO POUNDS OF VAPOR WAS RELEASED FROM THE TANK CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO DESTINATION.    CAUSE CODE:  499  NARRI: 5(4+9+0)) * (2+0) =130

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THE OUTER BOX WAS CRUSHED, CRACKING THE PLASTIC BATTERY CASE, ALLOWING THE ACID TO LEAK OUT.  WE ESTIMATE THAT ONE LITRE OF ACID SPILLED.  BAKING SODA WAS APPLIED TO THE SPILL TO NEUTRLIZE IT. WE REMOVED THE INNER BOX THAT CONTAINED THE BATTERY FROM OUR OUTER OVERPACK BOX. THE INNER BOX HAD A CORROSIVE, CLASS 8 LABEL ON IT. THERE WERE NO SHIPPING PAPERS, LABELING, MARKING, EMERGENY RESPONSE INFORMATION NOR OTHER INDICATORS ON THE OUTER BOX TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA BRYAN BUCHANAN.  SA PAUL KLIMAS WAS ENROUTE TO INSPECT THE FREIGHT.

DSR Geyer was loading a drum on to trailer 13-3581.  He was using the drum attachment to load a drum and while setting that drum down.  He mananged to nick the side of a drum already in the trailer with the edge of the forklift attachment.  The drum that he nicked started leaking.  The leak was only for a moment as the drum was flipped on to its side.  The leaking drum was then put into a recovery drum.
column169: DSR Geyer needs to be more careful with his forklift.
