column42: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column168: PACKAGE CENTER RECEIVED A PACKAGE PICKED UP BY A DRIVER AT A HOME IN DETROIT. THE PACKAGE WAS STOPPED BY THE AIR LOADER AND HAZMAT ACCEPTANCE AUDITOR. DESIGNATED RESPONDER RESPONDED. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE BOX CONTAINED AN UNDECLARED AMOUNT OF DRY ICE. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OF ANY KIND ON THE BOX. THE BOX CONTAINED FROZEN FISH WRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND SURROUNDED BY 1 LBS OF DRY ICE. PACKAGE STOPPED SECURED AND HM 10 AND 5800.1 BOTH COMPLETED. MANAGER NOTIFIED.

column42: DANGEROUS GOODS IN MACHINERY OR DANGEROUS GOODS IN APPARATUS
column168: PRELOAD EMPLOYEE NOTICED PACKAGE APPEARED TO BE WET ON SIDE OF CARDBOARD AND NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR.  HEATHER STRICKLAND (DESIGNATED RESPONDER & SUPERVISOR)RESPONDED TO THE PACKAGE, WHICH WAS NOT MARKED AS A HAZMAT IN ANY WAY.  THE CONTENTS APPEARED TO BE AN ENGINE LEAKING GASOLINE, PACKED WITH NEWSPAPER AND CARDBOARD.  RESPONDER REMOVED PACKAGE TO HAZMAT HOLD AREA AND FOLLOWED THE UNDECLARED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCESS.

THE FREIGHT WAS LOADED ON TOP OF A LONG SKID APPROXIMATELY 16 FT LONG AND AS THE DRIVER WAS PULLING THE LONG CRATE OUT THE FIBERBOARD BOX FELL ALONG WITH OTHER FREIGHT AND WAS CRUSHED.  KEVIN VICKERS ADVISED ME OF THE SPILL.  I CALLED RICHARD SEAMAN AND INFORMED HIM OF THE SPILL WHILE MR. VICKERS CONTAINED AND CLEANED THE SPILL.  THE CONTENTS WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM AND INITIAL REPORTS WERE SENT.

PASSENGER JOHN YOUNG CHECKED IN FOR FLIGHT 2186 ON 6/17/2006.  HE RENDERED A COOLER THAT WE QUESTION THE CONTENTS OF.  HE WAS TRAVELING TO ANCHORAGE AK.  HE TOOK HIS BAGS TO TSA FOR SCREENING.  UPON EXAMINATION TSA AGENT JONATHAN MOHR DISCOVERED A LARGE FIRECRACKER.  UPON FURTHER INSPECTION HE FOUND ANOTHER FIRECREACKER 2 BOOKS OF MATCHES, (1) MAGNESIUM STICK (4) COMPRESSED FULES TABLETS (TRIOXANE)(2)22 SHELLS (1) 223 SHELL AND 1 COMPRESSED WOOD ROAD FLAIR.  HE RELEASED THE ITEMS TO A NON FLYING FAMILY MEMBER.  JONATHAN NOTIFIED LEO WHO INVESTIGATED AND DID AN NCIC CHECK WHICH WAS NEGATIVE.
column169: WE PROIDE SIGNAGE AND ASK PASSENGERS IF THEIR BAG CONTAINS DAMAGEROUS GOODS.  I WOULD RECOMMEND A FINE FOR THIS GENTLEMEAN TO REMIND HIM IF THE NEED FOR COMPLAINCE.

column42: ORGANOPHOSPHORUS PESTICIDES, LIQUID, TOXIC, FLAMMABLE, FLASH POINT NOT LESS THAN 23 DEGREES C
column168: Wilbur-Ellis Company flatbed truck was southbound on FM Road 50. The roadway made a slight curve to the left which caused the load to shift. Two drums fell off the truck. Our company driver (Chad Berlan) said the load securement strap ratchet must have come loose.  The drums landed on the west (right) side of the road. About 32 gallons of Cheminova Methyl 4 EC was spilled entirely off the roadway in the dirt area adjacent to FM Road 50.  Wilbur-Ellis Company employees responded to the scene. The spilled insecticide, coniaminated soil and four inches of soil below the contamination line were placed in two salvage drums The drums will be disposed of as hazardous waste at an EPA approved facility.  The National Response Center was notified (Report #800495, Ms. Rawls).  The Texas Commission of Environmental Quality was also notified (Report #20061971, Jerri Henderson).  There is no above ground water in the area nor does the area drain into navigable waters.
column169: WILBUR-ELLIS COMPANY DRIVER WILL REVIEW LOADING, BLOCKING, BRACING AND SECUREMENT PROCEDURES.

ON 06/07/2006 AT 0305 HRS, TRAIN MASTER JUSTIN DAVIDSON OF RUSSELL, KY, REPORTED TO THE PSCC THAT THERE WAS A HISSING SOUND AND A STRONG ODOR OF CHLORINE IN THE AIR NEAR TANK CAR UTLX 920099.  THIS WAS REPORTED TO HIM BY A YARD CREW DOING SWITCHING DUTIES ON THE EAST END OF RUSSELL YARD.   THE EAST END OF THE YARD WAS ISOLATED TO PREVENT ANY TRAINS CREWS OR RAIL ROAD PERSONNELL FROM ENTERING THE EFFECTED AREA.  THE PSCC CONTACTED THE NRC AND CHEMTREC (REP. NUMBER 06072006018), WHO CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND CHLOREP FOR ASSISTANCE.  CSXT CONTACTED SPSI TO SINPECT THE SUSPECT LEAKING TANK CAR.  AT 0730 HRS, SPSI, BRENNTAG CHEMICAL AND CSXT MADE ENTRY TO THE RAIL CAR UTLX 920099.  JACK BAILEY OF SPSI REPORTED THAT THE A ED LIQUID LINE WAS LOOSE 3/4 OF A TURN AND THE PLUG WAS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  SPSI ALSO REPORTED THAT THE OTHER 3 VALVES WERE ALSO LOOSE ABOUT 1/4 OF A TURN EACH, AND 3 OF THE 4 PLUGS WERE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  ALL VALVES AND PLUGS WERE TIGHENED, THE CAR WAS SEALED AND RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.    CAUSE CODE: 662  NARRI: 5(4+10+2)X(2+)=160
column169: CSXT MANAGER OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WILL MEET WITH THE SHIPPER, DOVER CHEMICAL TO DISCUSS AND GO OVER THEIR SOP FOR THE SAFE TRANSPORTATION OF CHLORINE CARS.

WALTER MCBURROWS OF THE LIT / FAA WAS NOTIFIED AT 15:00 ON 6-12, AND HE WAS TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION.

THE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS IMPROPER LOADING, ANOTHER SHIPMENT WAS STACKED ON TOP OFF THE SHIPMENT.  WHEN WE LIFTED THE TOP SKID WE NOTICED THAT THE TOP OF ONE OF THE PACKAGES WAS WET.  WE THEN NOTICED THE SHIPMENT WAS HAZMAT AND CLOSED THE TRAILER DOOR AND CLEARED THE AREA AND CALLED INFOTRAC FOR THE MSDS AND THEN CALLED CONWAY SAFETY MANAGER BILL WRIGHT TO FIND OUT IF WE COULD CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  BILL THEN GAVE US THE OK, AND I PLACED THE BOX INTO A 20 GALLON SALVAGE DRUM WITH OVERPACK.  THE SCREW CAP ON ONE OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLES WAS CRACKED DUE TO THE STACKING AND THAT IS WHAT CAUSED THE SPILL TO OCCUR.

RUSSELL, A DRIVER FOR CON-WAY FREIGHT, WAS WORKING THE DOCK AT 19:00. HE WAS UNLOADING A TRAILER BY MEANS OF A FORKLIFT. THE MATERIAL WAS SET INSIDE THE TRAILER FOR THE SPECIFIC DESTINATION (GREENVILLE, SC). IT WAS A PAIL (5 GALLON) LOADED ON THE TRAILER NEAR THE BACK. ANOTHER DRIVER WORKING THE DOCK BACKED OUT OF THE TRAILER AND THE MOVEMENT OF THE DOCK PLATE CAUSED THE CORNER TO PUNCTURE THE PAIL. THE FORKLIFT CAUSED THE DOCK PLATE TO BOUNCE WHEN HE WAS BACKING OUT OF THE TRAILER WHICH CAUSED THE INCIDENT.
column169: DUE TO THE NATURE OF THIS INCIDENT NO CORRECTIVE ACTION WAS TAKEN. BOTH DRIVERS WERE INDIRECTLY INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT. WE LOAD SINGLE PAILS TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER TO PREVENT DAMAGE ON THE DOCK. NOW WE MOVE PAILS OUT OF HEAVY TRAFFIC AND NOT ON PARTIAL TRAILERS IN REAR AREA.

ON JUNE 21, 2006 WHILE LOADING A BAG ON AMERICAN AIRLINES FLIGHT 533 FROM ST. LOUIS TO LAS VEGAS AN EMPLOYEE NOTICED SMOKE COMING OUT OF A BAG. THIS WAS A CONNECTION BAG (TAG 367551) OFF INBOUND FLIGHT 5448 FROM TRANS STATES OUT OF JOPLIN. WHEN THE BAG WAS OPENED THE EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED A BOX OF DIAMOND STRIKE ANYWHERE MATCHES SMOLDERING. THE BOX CONTAINED 250 "STRIKE-A-FIRE" MATCHES, AND WELL OVER HALF OF THEM HAD BURNED AND THEN APPARENTLY EXTINGUISHED. THE EMPLOYEE DID NOT SEE ANY FLAMES HOWEVER IMMEDIATELY REMOVED IT FROM THE BAG. THE PASSENGER, DEBORAH ANN COX, WAS NOTIFIED AND IDENTIFIED THE CONTENTS AS BELONGING TO HER. THE CSM ON DUTY EXPLAINED TO HER THAT STRIKE ANYWHERE MATCHES ARE NOT ALLOWED ON AIRPLANES. MS. COX STATED SHE WAS NOT AWARE THEY WERE FLAMMABLE. THE BOX OF MATCHES WAS CONFISCATED AND THE PASSENGER WAS ALLOWED TO TRAVEL.

column58: Frangible Disc; Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: UPRR $ RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF TANK CAR UCLX 30001 REPORTEDLY STEAMING NEAR BEECH, IA. ERIC BAUER, SR. MTO REPORTED THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASING PRODUCT FROM THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE. MR. SEKAVEC RESPONDED TO THE HOUSE TRACK OFF OF THE SIDING AT BEECH AND INSPECTED THE CAR, FINDING THE FRANGIBLE DISK RUPTURED. AFTER CONFERRING WITH DAN THOMPSON, BASIC CHEMICAL, A REPLACEMENT FRANGIBLE DISK WAS INSTALLED IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE HOUSIN9. INSPECTION OF THE CAR ALSO INDICATED THAT THERE WAS SOME RESIDUAL PRODUCT CONTAINED TO THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR FROM THE DISK RUPTURING. AFTER SECURING THE DISK, MR. SEKAVEC PREPARED TWO AND ONE-HALF GALLONS OF BAKING SODA SOLUTION AND USED IT TO DECONTAMINATE THE CAR. AFTER SECUREMENT OF THE DISK, THE CAR WAS PLACED BACK INTO THE TRAIN AND CONTINUED IN TRANSPORTATION. NO REMEDIATION WAS NEEDED FOR THIS INCIDENT AS NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing; Valve Seat
column168: OUSMAN, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 79506 WAS LEAKIN9 FROM THE TOP. THE LIQUID WAS EVAPORATING AND NO MATERIAL HAD IMPACTED THE SOIL. MICHAEL MOORE, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED. ALL STATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. OUSMAN CONFIRMED THERE WERE NO FATALITIES, NO INJURIES, NO EVACUATIONS, NO WATERWAYS AFFECTED, AND NO DAMAGE TO THE TANK CAR.. THE TANK CAR REMAINED IN THE CONSIST. SIMON, REPRESENTING THE OWNER OF THE PRODUCT, QUADRA ENERGY TRANSPORTATION, WAS NOTIFIED AND ADVISED MICHAEL MOORE, MANA9ER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY TO MANAGE THE INCIDENT AND TOWARD THE BILL TO QUADRA ENERGY TRANSPORTATION. MR. MOORE ADVISED THE CAR WAS SHELL FULL AND THE PRESSURE DEVICE HAD RELEASED EXCESS PRESSURE. THE CAR WAS REMOVED FROM THE CONSIST AND WAS PLACED ON A SIDING UNTIL A LOAD REDUCTION COULD BE DONE. ON 06/30/2006 A TRUCK ARRIVED AND A UPRR CONTRACTOR REMOVED APPROXIMATELY 1000 GALLONS. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO ITS DESTINATION.

column62: Misaligned Material, Component, or Device; Deterioration or Aging
column168: FRA INSPECTOR NOTED TANK CAR RTMX 2385 LEAKING WHILE BEING HANDLED UNDER NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS, BAKERSFIELD, CA. THE CAR INFORMATION WAS GIVEN TO JOHN MAXWELL, CAR DEPT., FRESNO; CA. FOREMAN MAXWELL GAVE THE INFORMATION TO DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WHO WAS IN BAKERSFIELD AT THE TIME. INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR NOTED THE MAN WAY GASKET WAS DISTORTED BETWEEN THE MAN WAY COVER PLATE AND MAN WAY NOZZLE. UPON OPENING THE MAN WAY, THE GASKET WAS FOUND TO BE IN POOR CONDITION. THE RUBBER GASKET HAD CUTS IN SEVERAL PLACES, AND DISTORTED DUE TO BEING PINCHED BETWEEN THE COVER PLATE AND NOZZLE WHEN THE COVER PLATE WAS LOWERED. THE PORTION OF THE GASKET THAT HAD BEEN NEXT TO THE COVER PLATE HINGE HAD MOVED/DROPPED INSIDE OF THE NOZZLE WHEN THE CAR WAS SECURED FOR TRANSPORTATION. WHEN THE MAN WAY PLATE WAS TIGHTENED, THE TORQUE PINCHED AND DISTORTED THE GASKET, ALLOWING A GAP IN THE SEAL. A NEW GASKET WAS PLACED ONTO THE NOZZLE, AND THE COVER PLATE LOWERED TO PREVENT PINCHING OF THE GASKET. THE MAN WAY WAS PROPERLY SECURED. THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ENSURE PROPER CLOSURE, THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.
column169: PROPER SECUREMENT INSPECTION

column62: Abrasion; Dropped; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: Brad, Rail Terminal Services Manager, reported Container APLU 491805 had released an undetermined amount of product onto the concrete pad at Pad D259 in the Mesquite Yard, Mile Post 206.04 of the Dallas Subdivision. Brad stated the release was contained to the pad and was a very slow drip. Brad stated there were no injuries or exposures. Brad also stated no water ways had been nor would be impacted. Michael Moore, Manager of Chemical Transportation Safety, was notified and responded. All necessary state agencies were contacted. Moore advised there was a drip coming from the front left corner of the trailer. Approximately two gallons had leaked out and was contained with oil dry. A contractor was called to over pack the leaking drum and  remediate the area. Al 03:04 PM, Moore advised remediation was complete and the container was released to transportation.
